# First
I suggest the addition of `useKeep`.
There is no method in **React** that can centrally manage **localStorage**.
For this reason, we propose the following method.

## About
Simply put, it is a value-preserving version of useState.
It uses localStorage to hold values. 

### How to use

```tsx
import { useKeep, useEffect } from "/path/to/hooks"

export default function NumOfVisits(props: any) {
   
  const [visit, setVisit] = useKeep(0, "visitNumber");

  useEffect(() => {
    const increment = async () => {
      await setVisit(visit + 1);
    };

    increment();
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>{visit}</div>
  );

}
```

This number will increase by 1 with each visit.

### Tentative Code
I have written a tentative code for a situation that meets the specifications. It is as follows.

```typescript
import { useState } from "/parh/to/hooks";

function useKeep(iv, id) {
  const [v, setV] = useState(iv);

  if (!localStorage.getItem("_uk_")) {
    const ivl = {};
    ivl[id] = { v: iv, b: false };
    localStorage.setItem("_uk_", JSON.stringify(ivl));
    setV(iv);
  } else {
    const sv = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("_uk_")) || {};
    const vo = sv[id] || { v: iv, b: false };
    setV(vo.v);
  }

  function setVS(value) {
    setV(value);
    const s = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("_uk_")) || {};
    const vo = s[id] || { v: iv, b: false };
    vo.b = vo.v;
    vo.v = value;
    s[id] = vo;
    localStorage.setItem("_uk_", JSON.stringify(s));
  }

  return [v, setVS];
}

export { useKeep };

```

## Context

Trying to implement a generic Combobox following the [W3C pattern](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/combobox/examples/combobox-autocomplete-list/#rps_label) without bleeding the implementation details outside the component (trying to make so you can interact with it as you would a native component).
When the user selects a value either by clicking an option or pressing `Enter`, the value of the input changes and we would like to trigger a change event.

## Observation

With vanilla JavaScript, triggering an event in those situations is quite simple: 
```js
function onClick(event) {
  setValue(event.currentTarget.textContent)
  const event = new Event('change')
  input.dispatchEvent(event)
}
```
The equivalent in React would be something like:
```js
function onClick(event) {
  setValue(event.currentTarget.textContent)
  const event = // ???
  if (props.onChange) props.onChange(event);
}
```
But onChange on native HTML elements would be called with a SyntheticEvent which contains more than regular JS events.
It is not even possible to create objects to match the SyntheticEvent interface since the values for `target` and `currentTarget` (and probably `relatedTarget` too) are readonly but only set on event dispatch: 
```ts
export class ChangeEvent<T = Element> extends Event implements React.ChangeEvent<T> {
	nativeEvent: Event;
	private propagationStopped = false;
        // TS2564: Property 'target' has no initializer and is not definitely assigned in the constructor
	readonly target: SyntheticChangeEvent<T>['target'];
        // TS2564: Property 'currentTarget' has no initializer and is not definitely assigned in the constructor
	readonly currentTarget: SyntheticChangeEvent<T>['currentTarget'];

	constructor(
		target: SyntheticChangeEvent<T>['target'],
		/* global EventInit */
		options?: EventInit,
	) {
		super('change', options);
		this.nativeEvent = this;
		target.dispatchEvent(this);
	}

	isDefaultPrevented(): boolean {
		return this.defaultPrevented;
	}

	stopPropagation() {
		super.stopPropagation();
		this.propagationStopped = true;
	}
	isPropagationStopped(): boolean {
		return this.propagationStopped;
	}

	persist(): void {
		return;
	}
}
```

## Suggestion

Expose a way to create synthetic events.
These events are [created in React source code](https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/main/packages/react-dom-bindings/src/events/SyntheticEvent.js), maybe there is a way to export those functions ? Or maybe a cleaner way would be to convert concrete SyntheticEvents from types to classes to provide constructors ?

**Do you want to request a feature or report a bug?**

Feature/enhancement

**What is the current behavior?**

Currently the eslint plugin doesn't throw an error when you have unnecessary dependencies in the useEffect's dependencies array because this could be a legit case but in general these dependencies are unnecessary and could cause errors.

Example:
```typescript
React.useEffect(() => {
    if(legitDependency) {
         // some api call that in the past used nonLegitDependecy but in a refactor this was removed
    }
}, [legitDependency, nonLegitDependency]) // exhaustive-deps doesn't warn for nonLegitDependency in a useEffect
````
**What is the expected behavior?**

It'd be great if we could configure "eslint-plugin-react-hooks" rule to warn in these cases, because I think in the most of cases we don't want this effect runs for these unnecessary dependencies and they are there because a mistake.

```typescript
React.useEffect(() => {
    if(legitDependency) {
         // some api call that in the past used nonLegitDependecy but in a refactor this was removed
    }
}, [legitDependency, nonLegitDependency]) // eslint warn/error  React Hook React.useEffect has an unnecessary dependency: 'nonLegitDependency'. Either exclude it or remove the dependency array 
````
I've created this rule based on the exhaustive-deps code and I've found a lot hints with this. So I think it'd great and very useful for others projects to take advantage of this, if this was included in the "react-hooks/exhaustive-deps" rule.

As for how/where to configure it, we could add something like this to our .eslintrc:

```
'react-hooks/exhaustive-deps': [
    'error',
    {
        warnWithNonLegitDependencies: true,
    },
],
```

And then we could mark legit dependecies in this way:

```typescript
React.useEffect(() => {
    if(legitDependency) {
         // some api call that in the past used nonLegitDependecy but in a refactor this was removed
    }
}, [legitDependency, /* legit-dependency */ nonLegitDependency]) // No eslint errors
````

For this new behaviour, we only have to change [this condition](https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/d1c8cdae3b20a670ee91b684e8e0ad0c400ae51c/packages/eslint-plugin-react-hooks/src/ExhaustiveDeps.js#L1445 ) to save all unnecessary dependencies in a useEffect and create an extra check to omit dependencies with "legit-dependency" comment before them. I could create a PR for this, if you like.
